'''Margaret Catherine Alice Hyson''' (also known as '''M.C. Alice Hyson'''; '''Alice Hyson''') (Feb. 22, 1861–March 8, 1915)<ref name=Tombstone>{{cite web|title=M. C. Alice Hyson Tombstone|url=http://midatlantic.rootsweb.ancestry.com/HarrySenft/CemeteryDisk49/RoundHill/IMG_0338.JPG|website=Round Hill Cemetery|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[missionary]]. She spent 31 years as a missionary<ref name="Alice Hyson">{{cite book|last1=Yohn|first1=Susan|title=A Contest of Faiths: Missionary Women and Pluralism in the American Southwest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7PxklWKpqCoC&pg=PA129|pages=119–130|accessdate=June 26, 2014|isbn=0801482739|year=1995}}</ref> in the Western territories at a time when few white women were traveling to the West, to the [[Taos, New Mexico]] and [[Santa Fe de Nuevo México]] regions. Hyson would go on to build the John Hyson School in [[Chimayo, New Mexico]], now the only remaining elementary Presbyterian mission school left in New Mexico.<ref name=McRuiz>{{cite web|last1=McRuiz|first1=Michelle|title=A Light in Chimayo|url=http://horizons.pcusa.org/archives/2002/HrznNoDc02/Hyson.htm|publisher=John Hyson Educational Center|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> The mission at [[Ranchos de Taos, New Mexico]] was named for her: the Alice Hyson Mission, for her service to the [[Presbyterian Church of America]]. Aside from providing a religious and academic education, she also provided rudimentary health care.<ref name="Alice Hyson"/>

== Family ==

Born on 22 February 1861,<ref name=Cemetery/> Alice was the daughter of John Hyson and Margaret (Miller) Hyson, of Hopewell Township in [[York County, Pennsylvania|York County]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Alice Hyson was the seventh child of 14 children.   The family, devout Presbyterians of Scotch-Irish descent, attended the Round Hill Presbyterian Church in [[Stewartstown, Pennsylvania]].  Her siblings were:<ref name=Gibson>{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=John|title=A biographical history of York County, Pennsylvania|date=1975|chapter=Robert Bortner Hyson|publisher=Genealogical Pub. Co.|location=Baltimore|isbn=9780806306759|pages=629–630|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TMg4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA629|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>
* Jane Ann Hyson, 1848-1913
* John Miller Hyson, 1850-1931
* Elizabeth Mary Hyson, 1852-1921
* Robert Bortner Hyson, 1853-1930
* Sarah Mariah Hyson, 1855-1920
* Archibald Free Hyson, 1857-1945
* David A. Hyson, 1859-1936
* Cordelia Elwinda Hyson, 1863-1942
* Hanna Emma Abby Hyson, 1864-1947
* Clara Louisa Hyson, 1866-1889
* Zelia Gertrude Hyson, 1867–1931
* Pleasant C. Hyson, 1869–1967
* Bertha Olivia Hyson, 1873–1960

== Education ==

Alice Hyson and her thirteen siblings were educated at the Hyson School, a one-room school house located near their farm in rural [[York County, Pennsylvania|York County]].  Alice attended  [[Millersville University|Millersville Normal School]], along with her sisters.

== Missionary work ==

In 1884, at the age of 23, Alice was sent by [[Faith Haines]]<ref name="Alice Hyson"/>{{rp|108}} of the Women's Home Missionary Society of the Presbyterian Church, to the territory of New Mexico to begin her missionary service.<ref name=Foote>{{cite book|last1=Foote|first1=Cheryl J.|title=Women of the New Mexico frontier, 1846-1912|date=2005|publisher=University of New Mexico Press|location=Albuquerque|isbn=0826337554|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KUto8ByWtO4C&pg=PA92|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> The first school was a dark, poorly ventilated room in the house of Doña Antonia Montaño. Although the school was initially for boys only, Alice Hyson was able to reach girls as well by establishing a sewing class. "Then the mothers began to take as much pride in the girls as in the boys."<ref name=AyerYHoy>{{cite journal|last1=Bernal|first1=J. M.|title=Our Teacher, Alice Hyson|journal=Ayer y Hoy en Taos|date=1998|volume=Summer|pages=8–10|url=http://taoscountyhistoricalsociety.org/images/AyerYHoy/251998Summer.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>  After two years, the school moved to a small church.  Around 1888, a new school building was built, with two classrooms and teachers' quarters.<ref name=AyerYHoy/>

Alice Hyson devoted 31 years of services as a Presbyterian missionary teacher at the plaza schools in [[Taos, New Mexico]].<ref name="Alice Hyson"/>{{rp|110}} She is noted for her work at Ranchos de Taos, the Presbyterian funded school.  Her sisters Bertha and Cordelia also worked with her at various times.<ref name="Alice Hyson"/>{{rp|111}}

== Death == 
Alice Hyson lived and worked in Ranchos de Taos until her health began to decline in 1915.  Then she returned to her family in Pennsylvania.<ref name=AyerYHoy/> She died of cancer<ref name="Alice Hyson"/> on March 8, 1915, and was buried in Round Hill Presbyterian Cemetery, East Hopewell Township, York, Pennsylvania.<ref name=Cemetery>{{cite web|title=Round Hill Presbyterian Cemetery|url=http://midatlantic.rootsweb.ancestry.com/HarrySenft/CemeteryDisk49/RoundHill/AlphaIndex.htm|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>  Her epitaph reads: "For God is not unrighteous to forget your work and labor of love which ye have shewed toward his name".<ref name=Tombstone/>

